<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp4sec1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Fermat's Little Theorem</title>

  <p> </p>
  
<proposition xml:id="proposition-multiplication_by_relatively_prime_element_permutes_the_units">
  <title>Multiplication by relatively prime element permutes the units</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a, m \in \Z</m>, <m>m &gt; 1</m> is a positive integer, such that <m>\gcd(a,m)=1</m>, then multiplication by <m>a</m> permutes the elements of <m>U_m</m>.  In other words, the function <m>f: U_m \to U_m</m> defined by <m>f(x) = ax \pmod m</m> is a bijection.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      There are many ways to do this one.  Here is one way, but can you find others?  First, show that if <m>r\in U_m</m>, then <m>gcd(ar,m)=1</m>.  How??? Suppose <m> d </m> divides both <m>ar</m> and <m>m</m>.  If <m>d&gt; 1</m>, then there exists a prime <m>p</m> dividing <m>d</m> (why???).  Deduce a contradiction.  Next, suppose that <m>ar_1 \equiv ar_2 \pmod m</m> for some <m>r_1, r_2 \in U_m</m>.  Deduce that <m>r_1 \equiv r_2 \pmod m</m>.  You may find  <xref ref="proposition-relatively_prime_elements_are_units_modulo_n"/>, <xref ref="proposition-minimal_divisor_is_prime"/>, <xref ref="proposition-euclid_lemma"/>, <xref ref="definition-units_modulo_n"/>,  <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-congruence_cancellation_theorem"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<sage>
<input>
m = 100
a = 97
e = euler_phi(m)
print(pow(a,e,m))
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-generalized_fermat_little_theorem">
  <title>Generalized Fermat's Little Theorem</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a, m \in \Z</m>, <m>m &gt; 1</m> is a positive integer, such that <m>\gcd(a,m)=1</m>, then <m>a^{\phi(m)} \equiv 1 \pmod{m}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof. Let <m>r_1,\ldots,r_k</m> be the elements of <m>U_m</m>.  What is <m>k</m> and why? Analyze the product 
      <m> \prod_{i=1}^{k} ar_i = (ar_1)(ar_2)\cdots(ar_{k})</m> in two different ways (and do not forget that multiplication by <m>a</m> permutes the elements of <m>U_m</m> (why???)).  
      You may find  <xref ref="proposition-multiplication_by_relatively_prime_element_permutes_the_units"/>, <xref ref="definition-phi_function"/>, <xref ref="definition-units_modulo_n"/>, and <xref ref="definition-congruence"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<proposition xml:id="proposition-fermats_little_theorem">
  <title>Fermat's Little Theorem</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a, p \in \Z</m>, <m>p</m> is a prime, and <m>\gcd(a,p)=1</m>, then <m>a^{p-1} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      You may find  <xref ref="proposition-generalized_fermat_little_theorem"/>, <xref ref="proposition-phi_function_of_prime"/>, and <xref ref="definition-phi_function"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


</section>